b'' b'accounts of anti-armenian human right violations in azerbaijan b'prelude to current events in nagorno-karabakh' b'' b'+-----------------------------------------------------------+' b'| b'| they beat up the husband, dragged the wife outside, b'| and stood her naked next to our burning things; her b'| husband was lying at her feet on the ground. the crowd b'| shouted, "look at the naked armenian!" they were going to b"| throw the poor woman into the fire...mamma wouldn't allow b'| it but i went to the window and saw her standing there, b'| and they took skewers that had been heated in the fire b'| and stuck them into her body. b'| b'+-----------------------------------------------------------+' b'' b'depositions of:' b'' b'zinaida poghosovna hakopian' b'' b'born b'dispatcher' b'kavkazenergoremont electric booster station' b'' b'her daughters' b'' b'gayane (gaya) vazgenovna hakopian' b'born b'orderly' b'sumgait municipal hospital no. b'' b'diana vazgenovna hakopian' b'born b'second-year student' b'sumgait secondary school no. b'' b'residents at building apartment b'microdistrict no. b'sumgait [azerbaijan]' b'' b'' b'-zinaida: on march we arrived in yerevan, and the next day they registered' b'us at the train station and took us to the boarding house. the conditions were' b"wonderful, thanks to our armenians, who received us. but it's not relaxing all" b"the same. i don't know how everyone else feels about it, but for me it's" b"torture. we don't have a place to call our own. i had a two bedroom apartment" b"in sumgait, my children went to school and we lived well, in friendship. it's" b'painful that in our times, in in the soviet period, people can break' b"into our apartment and try to kill me and my children, in whom i've put all my" b'efforts and my whole youth. everything was going well for us: my older' b'daughter was studying at the institute, the middle one was preparing to enter' b'medical school and was interning as an orderly, and my youngest had been sick' b'for a long time, but had returned to health. i have been though a lot in my' b"life: it's been seven years since i lost my husband, i raised my children by" b"myself. lots of women have similar fates, but there's nothing to be done about" b"it. but i can't control myself when i remember what happened in sumgait on" b"february and it was just a horror, it's indescribable." b'' b"on february our relative, ira, came to visit us. she's better friends with" b'my oldest daughter, and so right away she asked, "where\'s vika?" i say,' b'"vika\'s off in pirkuli on a trip for three days, she\'s supposed to come back' b'tomorrow." my middle daughter, gaya, had baked a cake and we sat there talking' b'and laughing, drinking tea. then gaya and diana went to walk ira home.' b'' b'they left and a few minutes went by; suddenly i hear noise. i raced out to' b'the balcony--our balcony is right across from the bus station, we live at the' b'corner of mir and druzhba streets--i look and see that there are hoards of' b"people near the bus station and they're all shouting something. what they're" b"shouting i can't understand. our neighbor is standing on his balcony, too. i" b'ask, "nufar, what\'s happened?" he says, "i don\'t know, i can\'t figure it out' b'either." i got scared--the kids had gone outside, and i wanted to run after' b"them, but then there was a knock at the door. i open the door and it's the" b'kids. "mamma," says gayane, "you\'ll never believe what\'s going on out there!' b'it\'s awful!" ira says, "aunt zina, they\'re shouting, \'karabagh! karabagh!' b"karabagh is ours!' we didn't know what was going on. they're threatening to" b'drive out the armenians and slaughter them."' b'' b'i called my brother, and his wife answered the phone. i said, "aunt tamara,' b'don\'t worry, ira is staying here with us, and we\'ll see her home later." i' b"couldn't shut my eyes all night long, even until morning. i was worried about" b'vika. my god, what was going on, what had happened?!' b'' b'-gayane: that day, on the 27th, we stood on the balcony and observed what was' b"happening, although mamma wouldn't allow us to watch all of it. there weren't" b'50 yards between our building and the bus station. we could see and hear' b'everything perfectly. they were stopping buses, dragging people out, leading' b'all the passengers out, looking for armenians. if they found an armenian on' b"the bus, then it started .i don't know what to call it b'' b"-zinaida: it's called slaughter." b'' b"-gayane: the mob would descend on people and beat them. i don't know if they" b'were killing them or not, but when they left them, they lay still, not moving,' b'as though nothing was left of them. one person was lying there and they' b'started dragging him. the police were standing right there, to the side, not' b"doing anything, they didn't take any steps to calm that mob." b'' b'it was awful to stand there and watch it all from the balcony. and you' b"couldn't go anywhere, somehow you wanted to be able to see everything" b'so as to tell of it later. we wanted to leave sumgait that day. what kept us' b'was the idea that we live in the soviet union, and that something would be' b'done about it. where in the world was our government?!' b'' b"-zinaida: we couldn't leave town, of course, because our older daughter wasn't" b'home. and at the same time i was terrified for gaya and diana. on sunday' b'morning when i went to see ira home, our neighbor said, "zin\', you know they' b"went into valodya's house and smashed everything he had. they murdered his" b'father and two sons." valodya is our neighbor, he\'s an armenian, he lives on' b'the first floor. i think, my god, what is happening?! and in broad daylight!' b'' b'i saw ira home and when on the way back i came across a mob shouting "slay the' b'armenians! karabagh is ours!" this was at o\'clock in the afternoon. on the' b'way i stopped into a bread store and the saleswoman says, "they beat our store' b'manager, they thought he was an armenian and they beat him, but he was an' b'azerbaijani." and i asked, "did they kill him?" she says, "no, he\'s in serious' b'condition." i left there and started to walk home on that same street, but the' b'mob started moving in my direction. i turned off the street and went down the' b'little way that goes toward the sputnik store. there i met another crowd, but' b"these weren't bandits, these were our people from sumgait. i was so frightened" b"that i walked without knowing where was going, i couldn't feel my legs or the" b'ground under my feet. i was walking and there was a boy standing before my' b'eyes. this was on the 27th, around evening time. he ran under our balcony, and' b'the mob surged toward him shouting, "he\'s an armenian, get him!" he wore a' b'black coat. they grabbed him, that boy, near the bus stop, i saw it. they' b'grabbed him by the legs and struck his head on the asphalt.' b'' b"i made it home but i just couldn't calm down. my oldest daughter was in my" b"thoughts. i was thinking, my daughter's coming home now, they'll stop her bus" b"and she'll be gone. there's no police, no protection, nothing. it's like they" b"had all died, there's no one, nothing, no authorities whatsoever. i can't even" b'find the words for it! i look and see an ikarus arriving. before going to the' b'bus station they stop near our place, across from the kosmos movie theater. so' b'this ikarus stops there and the gang is yelling, the azerbaijanis are running' b'toward it yelling, "armenians out!" and i see them take the armenians and beat' b"them, killing them. i can't watch it any more. it was a nightmare. i just" b"couldn't watch it. but gaya was standing there watching it, and i scolded her." b'she says, "mamma, i have to see it, i have to know what\'s happening, i have to' b'see it with my own eyes so i can tell our people of it later. so our children' b'will know."' b'' b'gayane: we saw a great deal on the 27th. they caught no less than people' b"before my eyes. i can't say for sure if they killed them or not b'' b"-zinaida: there were too many people there, the mob was too big. you couldn't" b'make anything out. but i saw that boy in the black coat with my own eyes. he' b'was or years old.' b'' b'-gayane: i think he was older, probably, about a tall fellow, a big guy,' b'in a coat. he was walking quickly, but when they shouted that he was an' b'armenian, he tore off running. and the mob went after him. they caught him' b"right under our balcony. i don't know. i don't think there could have been" b'much left of him after that. you can imagine what happens when a crowd attacks' b'one person. it was a mob, big, angry, and featureless. you know, there was a' b'similarity in the way they were dressed, mostly they were wearing long black' b"coats. you couldn't even tell them apart, they were all wearing black and they" b'all looked alike.' b'' b'-zinaida: when they picked up that boy and struck him against the asphalt and' b'he cried "mamma!" i ran into the room. i couldn\'t watch any longer. an awful' b"lot was going on right then, in various places, it wasn't only that boy," b"several people were being beaten up. you couldn't see all of it at once, but" b'when that boy cried "mamma!" i immediately started watching only him.' b'' b'-gayane: on that first day it went on from about six in the morning until' b'twelve at night. at midnight they dispersed and the police took their place.' b'they were scattered about in all districts. but how can you explain the fact' b'that by morning, when it had already started getting light, around seven' b"o'clock, our police were gone? the police disappeared and yielded their" b'positions to the bandits. in the morning they started gathering at our inter-' b'section again, at the bus station and at the entrance to downtown. from' b'morning on all the roads and mass transit stops were covered, and by nine' b"o'clock you couldn't even see the ground. there were thousands of people in" b'the crowd. again they began stopping vehicles and checking for armenians.' b'' b'-zinaida: they had signals. i realized that when i noticed that they made a' b'cross with their arms, they crossed their arms over their heads. the cross,' b'evidently, meant that the vehicle had armenians in it. they let the' b'azerbaijani cars through, and they stopped the armenian ones and started' b'their pogrom.' b'' b'-gayane: they stopped a white zhiguli and asked the driver what his' b'nationality was. he got out and said they were from baku. "but what is your' b'nationality?" he says armenian. they immediately start shouting, "ermeni,' b'ermeni!" and he says, "what\'s going on? i\'m coming from baku. i don\'t live' b'in sumgait." "doesn\'t matter, who cares if you\'re from baku or sumgait."' b'anyway the crowd pounced on him and started beating him, and they dragged a' b'woman--his wife, probably--out of the car. at this point the police came and' b'took the two and led them away. then the mob started smashing the car, and' b'then burned it. the flames blazed it was a horrible fire! then everyone' b'ran away, they thought the car was going to explode. about minutes later' b'another car comes along, a green moskvich. they ran up shouting "ermeni!' b'ermeni!" but this time they didn\'t pull the people out of the car, they didn\'t' b'beat them. maybe they burned them along with the car, because no one emerged' b'from the flames. the neighbor boy vakhit was standing on the balcony too,' b'acquaintances of his walked by below, and he asked them and they said, "yes,' b'they burned them along with the car." about two hours later a whole wedding' b'procession came by, and there was a doll on the first car. we thought they' b'were armenians, but the cars started to honk loudly. they were azerbaijanis,' b'and they were immediately allowed through.' b'' b"-zinaida: the driver waved his hand as if to say 'get out of the way.' the" b'whole crowd parted and the procession passed through freely.' b'' b'-gayane: by the way, at the marriage hall, which is right in the courtyard' b'of our building, there was a wedding that day. the azerbaijanis were cele-' b'brating and dancing. on the streets there was grief and death, people were' b'being killed, and people were celebrating the whole time.' b'' b'-zinaida: before the apartment itself was attacked i asked gaya to call and' b'find out when the tourist bus was supposed to arrive. she went to her' b"girlfriend's in the building, she lives in the first entryway, on the third" b'floor. gaya came back and said, "mamma, the bus is supposed to come around' b'eight, after eight." you can imagine what i was feeling, how hard it was:' b'vika knew nothing about what was happening and was coming to meet her death.' b'then i heard shouting. i raced to the window and see that the belongings of' b'our neighbors from the second entryway are being thrown outdoors. they were' b'thrashing about with the pillows and the feathers were lying like snow. i' b"started to cry. i am walking around the room, crying, wailing: vika's not" b'here, what will come of her gaya, of course, was consoling me: "mamma,' b"nothing will happen to her, don't worry, calm down, she's in good company," b'they\'ll look out for her."' b'' b'diana: i saw the green car burn. the car was burning when we went out onto the' b'balcony. gaya pushed me away, telling me to get off the balcony. i left. then' b'they came up to the balcony and asked if there were any armenians here.' b'' b"-zinaida: you're right, i forgot about that, that was on the 27th." b'' b"diana: there's a small, grassy area in front of our balcony; there are trees" b'planted there. the mob asked if there were any armenians in the building.' b"all the neighbors said, no, there are no armenians here. there weren't a lot" b"of armenians in our building, but there weren't just a few armenian families," b'either.' b'' b'-gayane: they fell upon the apartments on the 28th. there were terribly many' b'of them. our courtyard is huge, and it was completely filled with them.' b'' b'-zinaida: katusev had made an appearance on television earlier. he said that' b'two people, azerbaijanis, had been killed in karabagh. and when he said that' b'. you know how bees sound, have you heard how they buzz? it was like the' b'buzzing of millions of bees and with this buzzing they flew into our' b"courtyard, howling and shouting. i don't know how to describe it. by this" b'point we were afraid to watch from the balcony, but when i looked out of the' b'bedroom window--the znaniye bookstore is down there, and armenians live on the' b'second and fourth floors--i saw their things being thrown out the windows. i' b'realized that they would be upon us any minute. i shouted to gayane, "gaya,' b'hide the gold." that\'s honestly what i told my child. i grabbed diana. i' b"didn't know what to do! vika still wasn't home, and it was already getting" b'dark. i was afraid to look at the time because i was already horrified as it' b'was.' b'' b'-gayane: just in case, we changed the television channel from the moscow' b'station to the azerbaijani one.' b'' b'-zinaida: and turned it up loud.' b'' b"-gayane: we never listened to azerbaijani music. it just didn't do much for" b'us. in all those years we almost never listened to it. but sometimes we would' b'watch some entertainment show or film on azerbaijani television. and that was' b'it. and here we had it turned up full blast. so they would think we were' b'azerbaijanis.' b'' b"-zinaida: well you can imagine, they're slaughtering armenians, robbing them," b"and we're listening to this concert music from baku. our azerbaijani neighbors" b'suggested we do it, they knocked on the door and told gaya to turn on' b'azerbaijani music. but we already had it on anyway. turn on the lights, they' b"told us, so they will think you're not armenians. they're saying the armenians" b"are afraid to turn on their lights, they're hiding." b'' b'-g