. it worked out better that way. we were' b'the only armenian family in the fourth entryway. this gave us hope: we were' b"the only ones, the neighbors wouldn't let them in. they, the azerbaijanis," b'would fear for themselves and for their children. i looked and saw someone' b'crawling up on the balcony from below, it was easy to get up onto our balcony.' b'when we would lose the keys the neighbors would let up into their places and' b'we would crawl across onto our balcony and get in that way. so i turned around' b'and saw a guy with a knife on our balcony. he looks at me and shouts, "what' b'nationality are you here?"' b'' b'-zinaida: at the same time they were knocking on the door.' b'' b'-gayane: "what nationality are you?" he\'s shouting. well at first i was' b'frightened, but then i got control of myself and answered in perfect' b'azerbaijani, "you should be ashamed of yourself, asking a question like that.' b"can't you see i'm an azerbaijani? if i were an armenian would i come out to" b'meet you face to face and look you in the eyes?" he looks at me and tells the' b'people with him, "yes, azerbaijanis live here." from below they tell him,' b'"check it out, it can\'t be, they have to be armenians." and he asks me again,' b'"what nationality are you?" i say, "can\'t you see?" i started fuming. i could' b'not say anything else. "you\'re blind, that\'s for sure! you can yell all you' b'want, but that won\'t make us armenians." i hear them breaking down our' b'door, and mamma went toward the door. i say, "i don\'t have time to deal' b'with you, they\'re breaking down our door." go to the door and ask, "who is' b'it?" they answer, "open up!" i say, "wait, why are you breaking the door?' b'what\'s going on? i\'m opening up." we never locked the lower lock, it was' b"broken, but now they had locked it out of fear, and i couldn't get it open. i" b"say wait, i'm looking for the key. i opened the door--it was almost broken" b'down already. i opened the door and they bu