ey\'re armenians." well the other two convinced him, i don t know' b'how, and all the rest of them listened to them too. there were about of' b'them, if not more, all in our three-room apartment, even the entryway was' b'filled. they started leaving. yes, we\'re lezgins, we\'re lezgins." they started' b'leaving, and one of them took our tape recorder with him. and the one who had' b'first called us lezgins says, "leave that, what are you doing?" they seemed to' b'obey that guy.' b'' b'-gayane: he was tall, wearing baggy jeans and a coat.' b'' b'-zinaida: with a little moustache, i think.' b'' b"-gayane: no, he didn't have a moustache, he was tall with brown hair, he" b"wasn't a bad-looking sort. he didn't have anything in his hands." b'' b'-zinaida: he stood at the threshold.' b'' b"-gayane: yes, he didn't look like a bad guy, and you know, his face seemed" b"familiar to me. i had seen him somewhere. and more than once. but i can't" b'remember where. when he came in i was stupefied, i had a premonition that he' b"wouldn't be able to remain indifferent. when he said that we were lezgins and" b'that they should leave, such gladness started to glow inside of me. hope. they' b'continued to argue on their way out. some said, "they\'re armenians all the' b'same." and that fellow answered, "even if they are armenians, it\'s shameful,' b"the father died, they're mourning, there's nothing but women in the house," b'there\'s no men. we should stay out of the apartment." "what do you mean, stay' b'out? we can go in there!" and he said, "no, we should stay out, they\'re' b'lezgins, we\'re leaving here." the three of them protected us.' b'' b'-zinaida: no, the two of them. the one in the short coat and the one in the' b'grey suit, who stood at the threshold, about or years old. well they' b'were all young really. the two of them defended us.' b'' b'-diana: three, three!' b'' b'-zinaida: do you remember the third one, diana?' b'' b'-diana: yes, he was wearing dark clothes.' b'' b'-gayane: the third one was the one who came back. he wore a long brown coat.' b'' b'-diana: he wore a long, darkish brown coat, and his hair was dark too. when' b'they left, they told him downstairs that those women were armenians, and ran' b'back and said that they were going to kill us.' b'' b'-zinaida: they had all left, and we had started to calm down a little, and i' b'closed the door. and then there is a knock. i told gaya, "take diana and go' b'into the other room." my daughters went into the dining room, and i opened the' b'door. there was a guy there who said, "run, hide! they\'re coming to kill you' b'now!" we ran up to the third floor. we had some good neighbors up there,' b'azerbaijanis. i sent the kids and stood there alone, not knowing what to do.' b"i was so far gone out of a whole room i couldn't even think of anything" b'to take. i even forgot to take my work documents; at the time i had been' b"preparing a report to send to baku, and the documents were at home. i couldn't" b'see anything i could only see vika, my older daughter. i sent gaya and' b'diana upstairs, and stood there asking that fellow, "should i close the door' b'and leave everything like this?" he says, "what do you mean, door? get out of' b'here, they\'re coming to kill you! what are you standing there for?" and i ran' b'after the children.' b'' b'-gayane: we barely had time to get up to the third floor when they burst into' b'our apartment and started shouting, "where are the armenians?" we were already' b"at the neighbors'. they had an infant at the time, and the neighbor said," b'"don\'t you worry, i\'m not letting anyone in this apartment no matter what."' b'' b'-zinaida: on the third floor there i started asking the folks, our neighbors,' b"to go meet vika. the bus was due to arrive at eight o'clock. i dissolved in" b"tears, gaya was soothing me, diana was next to us, she was crying too, and i'm" b"already thinking that i've lost my older daughter, but deep in my heart i" b"still believe she's alive and my tears choked me. i was going out of my" b'mind. but no one could leave the building, the courtyard was packed with' b'people, swarming with them. from the balcony the neighbor in whose apartment' b'we were hiding asked the bandits, "where are those armenians, the ones who' b'were at home? where did they make off to?" they told him they didn\'t know.' b'they asked him where he lived. he answered, "can\'t you see, on the third' b'floor." he asked them specially to divert attention from his own apartment. we' b'heard them taking free reign of our apartment, and they threw our color' b'television off the balcony and it exploded.' b'' b'-gayane: mamma was crying the whole time. she fell into a faint and we brought' b'her around and held her back, because the whole time she kept making for the' b'door to go outside, alternately raving and sobbing, shouting, and calling' b"vika. she didn't notice us, probably because we were next to her. her thoughts" b'were only on vika. the neighbors who were hiding us were calming her too,' b'offering tea.' b'' b'-zinaida: we are very grateful to them. thanks to them my children and i are' b'alive, well, and unharmed. when they were throwing our belongings out and' b'burning them--the beds, the pillows, and the chairs--our neighbor came to us' b'and said, "how lucky you are that it\'s not you standing there naked, but some' b"other woman instead. you're from our part of the building you lost your" b"husband, you have children, thank god you're not in her position, we wouldn't" b'have been able to take it. i don\'t know what i would do." he of course' b"wouldn't have done anything, he was just trying to calm us down. in the yard" b'they were torturing our neighbors, fellow armenians they lived on the fifth' b'floor, in the third entryway. a married couple, vanya and nina, and their' b'three children. their last name is v. they hid their two daughters, and stayed' b'with their son to defend themselves, they even got boiling water ready, and an' b'axe, and held them off for a long time, but the they beat up the' b'husband, dragged the wife outside, and stood her naked next to our burning' b'things; her husband was lying at her feet on the ground. the crowd shouted,' b'"look at the naked armenian!" they were going to throw the poor woman into the' b'fire. the neighbors came out, an azerbaijani woman threw her a scarf, and she' b'covered herself with it, and the neighbors led her off to their apartment.' b'all the neighbors saw and heard it b'' b"-gayane: mamma wouldn't allow it but i went to the window and saw her standing" b'there, and they took skewers that had been heated in the fire and stuck them' b'into her body. our neighbor, who lived in the same entryway as nina--she' b'lives with us in the same boarding house now--saw what they had done, nina' b'showed her, from her knees up, almost up to her neck, her whole body was' b'covered, riddled, with wounds.' b'' b'-zinaida: in the morning, during the night of the 29th, rather, after one' b"o'clock, two buses approached the station. i wanted to run out. by then i" b"didn't care any more if i lived or died, but gayane wouldn't let me go, and" b'the neighbors said that i would bring disaster to them and they would be' b'slain along with their children. gaya was crying and said that i forgot about' b'them, my other children, but i could only think of vika. i imagined her torn' b"to pieces, i'm a mother, and they're just children, they don't understand i" b'would have jumped off the balcony and run to the soldiers for help. i was' b'going to do it but gayane wouldn\'t let me: "mamma, please! mamma, i beg of' b'you!" the neighbors were sleeping and gayane woke them with her cries. so we' b'held on that way till morning.' b'' b'on the morning of the 29th i told our neighbor i was going to go downstairs to' b'our apartment, maybe vika was lying there, murdered. he told me he would go' b'himself. he was gone for about five minutes, but it seemed like an eternity to' b'me. he returned and said there was no one there, nothing. i went down too,' b'stole down like a mouse, and slipped in everything was thrown all about. i' b"didn't go to the soldiers because the armored personnel carriers were far" b'away, farther than the bus station. i began looking for the briefcase with my' b'work in it. i was miserable because of my daughter, and at the same time' b'because of my work. my documents were there, my travel papers--i worked in the' b'transport division and my trip sheets.' b'' b'-gayane: mamma is a very responsible person, she was always ready to work' b'around the clock to do her job.' b'' b"-zinaida: i look around and i can't find the briefcase. i didn't care about" b'the fact that everything had been stolen out of all three of my rooms, that' b'everything was smashed, and the furniture was broken, i worried about that' b'later, but at first i was concerned about the lost documents. i went into the' b'kitchen. my daughter had hidden some valuables in the gas stove: my ring and' b'my earrings. it was all there. five minutes passed and gayane ran in and said,' b'"mamma, hurry." and diana came downstairs too. gayane found her coat among' b'the debris, and diana found her track shoes, her coat, and some of her' b'dresses.' b'' b'-diana: immediately after we got back up to the neighbors they started' b'throwing things around in the apartment under us. they threw a television onto' b'the asphalt, it exploded so violently it sounded like a thunderclap. then,' b"when vika wasn't there, i wouldn't eat, and they forced me, but i couldn't" b'eat. because i loved vika terribly and she and i had always gone to the movies' b'and gone for walks in the park. when we went into our apartment the next day' b'and everything was broken, right away i started looking for my dolls and my' b"books, but i didn't see anything. when we went back upstairs i managed to take" b"two cups from my tea service, and gaya took vika's suit and one of her own" b'dresses. my italian boots were gone, my brown coat, it was beautiful, there' b"wasn't a one of my beautiful dolls, and my giant lion was gone too, the one" b'that had been on top of the television. he was very large and very handsome.' b'i had two satchels, one for first grade and the other for second grade, one' b"was yellow-green with a boy and a girl on it, they're playing a drum and a" b'violin, and there is a dog sitting there closing its ears, and on the other' b'one were the letters a, b, c, d, e and the numbers two girls and a boy' b'with their mouths open like they are singing. they were beautiful satchels.' b'they were gone too. i had many books, i collected them, they were in the' b'bedside tables. and a boy had given me a little apron and a headband for my' b"birthday, they weren't around either. and i had some big books, fat ones, and" b'they disappeared, only one was left, the malachite box. the adventures of' b'karlson, pippi longstockings, and fairy tales of the world were left. all the' b'other books were gone.' b'' b'-zinaida: i continued searching for my briefcase, and then my supervisor' b"arrived. he had waited for me until nine o'clock, but i didn't appear, and he" b"thought something must have happened, so he came. he's a russian, aleksei" b'semyonovich lomakin. alik aliyev, the mechanic, came with him. when they saw' b'my wrecked apartment they were just petrified, they could not say a thing.' b'when i saw them i started crying. my azerbaijani neighbors came in. some of' b'them were crying, others were helping me pick up. i go on looking for my' b'documents and at the same time put things into the wardrobe. now that i' b"remember it it's both funny and painful: how could i have thought that i had" b'returned to my apartment and that everything had gone back to normal?' b'incidentally, later, when i went back to the apartment again those things were' b'gone too. and the door was gone. after my supervisor left, in the afternoon,' b'the neighbor said that we should leave, find another refuge. "i\'m afraid," he' b'said, "that someone saw you come to my apartment, and that they could kill you' b"and us too. my god, where could i go it was daytime and those i don't" b'even know what to call them, the bandits, those marauders, those jackals, i' b"don't know what to call them, i can't find the words, they were everywhere." b'where should i go with two girls? when i opened the door i had tears in my' b'eyes, and i was terrified and he said, "go to alik\'s, he\'s an' b'azerbaijani, too." and i say, "you should have said that earlier, when my' b'supervisor was here with the car, he could have taken us with him." everyone' b'feared for their own lives. what could i do? i went out into the entryway and' b'stood. and he says, "any other time i would keep you here a year, or two. but' b'right now, i\'m sorry then another door opened, also on the third' b'floor. i ask the neighbor, "tayara, can we hide at your place?" she\'s an' b'azerbaijani too. she says, "what kind of question is that? come in!" she hid' b'us. there were many people in the courtyard, and gaya and i hid in the' b'wardrobe, and they put diana under a mattress, leaving a small opening so the' b'child could breathe. tayara said that when the bandits left she would let us' b'out, and when they came back she would hide us again.' b'' b'we sat in the wardrobe for about a half hour. gaya became ill, and i allowed' b"her to get out. my legs fell asleep and felt like cannons. we hadn't eaten or" b'drunk anything for so long, since the 27th, when we saw that horror--and all' b"of it just snapped in me. tayara's husband went outside, even though i begged" b"him to stay, saying there should be a man in the house. he said that he'd be" b'in the courtyard, and if anything happened his wife would signal him. she put' b'her passport and all of their documents on the table so if they suddenly came' b'in she could show them that they were an azerbaijani family. my girls went to' b'the window--and what was going on out there! i feared for my children, that' b'someone would recognize them from the street. gaya let her hair down and put' b'on a scarf so she would resemble an azerbaijani, but directly across there was' b'a 9-story building, their windows were right across from us, and i shouted' b'that someone would see her and give us away on the spot. but she kept on' b'looking.' b'' b'-diana: i watched too.' b'' b'-zinaida: downstairs the bandits were fighting with the soldiers. the soldiers' b"didn't shoot, they didn't have orders to. i saw them throwing rocks at" b'the soldiers, they were young boys, and 19-year olds, and they defended' b"themselves i'm a mother after all, and they were no different from my" b'children. when one of the soldiers fell and his head started bleeding i had to' b"stop looking, l couldn't watch anymore i imagined my children in their" b'shoes b'' b'-gayane: the troops had assumed their defense that morning and had cordoned' b'off the buildings, and some of the soldiers surrounded the bus station, block' b'36, and our microdistrict but they only cordoned them off from the outside.' b'the mob fell upon the soldiers, who started to protect themselves, and the mob' b'surged into the courtyard with the soldiers after it. they caught several' b'azerbaijanis and started beating them with their clubs. one fell down and they' b"cracked open another's head b'' b"-zinaida: they show lebanon on television, and the war in afghanistan--that's just" b'what it was like. like in america, how they attack demonstrations with shields' b"and clubs--that's just how it was in our courtyard." b'' b"-gayane: don't compare it with america, those were peaceful demonstrations," b'but these?!' b'' b'-zinaida: but how could it happen here and not off somewhere in america! they' b"attacked the soldiers, hurled stones at them then i thought, where's the" b'tear gas that the americans use to disperse demonstrators? if they had used' b'gas on those jackals they all would have scattered.' b'' b'-gayane: they would not have scattered. the soldiers had been there since' b"morning, they didn't bring in fresh troops. they hadn't eaten, they were fine" b"standing there for about three hours, but then they got tired. they weren't" b'even allowed to sit down at noon they, the soldiers, attacked them, and' b'then the tables were turned. the mob went after the soldiers, the guys were' b'bunched into a group in the center street and covered themselves with their' b'shields, and the azerbaijanis surrounded them and threw paving stones at them.' b'and those guys sat there covering themselves with their shields. and meanwhile' b'tanks with machine guns were cruising the streets they always say, "our' b'children have never seen war." i never even dreamed about it, there was no' b'need to. but then i thought about those people who had lived through a war. it' b'was truly horrible the guys were tired, exhausted, some had had their' b'clubs taken away, others, their shields, they had been beaten, they were' b'covered in blood so many died! they beat the soldiers with their own' b"clubs and shields. and those guys stood there and couldn't defend themselves," b"they couldn't open fire. they couldn't even defend themselves, let alone us." b"it's comical b'' b'-zinaida: what are you saying? how can it be funny?' b'' b"-gayane: no, i didn't mean that: how could something like that happen during" b"our soviet period? it's painfully embarrassing! and they burned the armored" b'personnel carriers, too. someone shouted, "get away, it\'s going to blow!"' b'everyone scattered away, and the armored personnel carrier exploded. the' b'soldiers lost their senses. and when they drove the personnel carrier and the' b'bus at the mob out of rage and fury, they drove right up on the sidewalk.' b'' b'-zinaida: the bus that had brought the troops. only the driver was in it. the' b'bus ran over three people straight off, i saw it. and two armored personnel' b'carriers ran over four more. all in one or two minutes. the bus ran over' b'three, one of the carriers ran over two, and the second, two more. right on' b"our street there's a dry cleaners and appliance and watch repair places; one" b'of the armored personnel carriers went that way, and they say it ran over' b'several over there, too. but they ran over seven before our eyes. then the bus' b'ploughed into a book kiosk.' b'' b'-gayane: no, that was a flower place. it was a new booth. he drove straight' b'into it.' b'' b'-zinaida: the driver jumped out and they dragged the vehicle out to the' b'middle of the road and set it on fire.' b'' b'-gayane: and i also saw the troops put a bunch of azerbaijanis in a bus and' b'take them in a convoy to baku. there were many arrests.' b'' b"-zinaida: our neighbor, the one who hid us, couldn't take it, and he told his" b'wife that we should leave. they were running around in the courtyard looking' b'for the armenians. they knew that they were hiding with azerbaijanis, and they' b'were saying that they were going to check the azerbaijani families. poor' b'tayara got scared too, and started to cry; i pleaded with her, i said that i' b'would remember forever how she saved my children and me, but where could we' b'go?' b'' b"-gayane: she didn't make us leave, she said that she would do anything, but" b'she was afraid.' b'' b'-zinaida: i told tayara that we would just stay a little longer and that at' b'night we would return to our apartment. then her husband came back and said' b'that a curfew had been imposed. he says, "zina, you owe us a drink. gorbachev' b'announced a curfew." and bagirov [first secretary of the communist party of' b'azerbaijan ssr] was on television, he said that two people had been killed in' b'karabagh, but nothing was wrong, automobile windows had been broken, but there' b"hadn't been any killings. he kept making statements, and there were" b'azerbaijani songs and dances. tayara turned the tv all the way up. when we' b'learned of the curfew we calmed down, but then a crowd ran into the courtyard' b'again, a large one. our neighbor told them that there had been only one' b'armenian family here, but they had already killed them all, there was no one' b'left. we hid in the wardrobe again. and they stuck diana back under the bed.' b'' b'-gayane: tayara went down to our apartment to see what was happened there, and' b'found two bandits. they asked her, "what are you doing here" tayara answered,' b'"i came to take something for myself." "take all you want, they\'re gone now."' b'' b'-zinaida: yes, she had wanted to get something for us, at least some bedding.' b'she said, "what are you going to do, empty handed, naked, with three children,' b'nothing remains of your entire apartment." in short, we calmed down, and the' b"crowd raced off to the other building, the one across from us. i don't know" b'what went on there.' b'' b'-gayane: the curfew had its effect on the gangs, many started to disperse:' b"they were warned that they would open fire on them. the soldiers didn't know" b"the city, they couldn't get oriented, they drove up and down the main streets," b"but didn't go into the courtyards. when we were at the city party committee" b'they asked people from sumgait to go with them and show them the way.' b'' b'-zinaida: the tanks entered the city on the night of the 29th.' b'' b'-gayane: no, mamma, the tanks had been there earlier, but were near the city' b'party committee, where the armenians were after midnight, on march b'when i had finally gotten to sleep after two sleepless nights, mamma said,' b'"get your things together, they have sent buses for us." as it was we had been' b'dressed the entire time. mamma went to check it out .and came back for us.' b'' b'-zinaida: when i came back for the children tayara said that vika was alive' b'and well, some guys had come and told her that they had hidden her in a safe' b"place. i both believed it and didn't believe it. we ran out to the tanks. the" b'gambarians were there, roman and sasha; their father, shurik, the clarinetist,' b'was killed, and their mother was there. sasha came over and asked about the' b'girls. i was surprised, how did he know my girls? he said that he knew me and' b'the girls. our neighbor himself went for gaya and diana and it seemed like he' b'was taking forever so i went after him. another neighbor came out, anna' b'vasilyevna, a russian: "zinochka, my dear, goodbye and good luck." she kissed' b'diana. they put us in the bus and the captain gave the order for us to be' b"taken to the city party committee. the bus wouldn't start, so they put us on" b'another one. it was pouring rain.' b'' b'-diana: when they imposed the curfew there were many soldiers on the streets,' b'and they all had clubs and shields. and when the azerbaijanis attacked them,' b'many of the soldiers died. they threw paving stones--huge rocks--at the' b'soldiers. i saw this myself. the soldiers ran over those azerbaijanis with the' b'tanks. the soldiers saw that the azerbaijanis were doing violence to people' b'and they ran over them out of rage. we got scared and they hid me under a' b'mattress and a blanket, and gaya and mamma crawled into the wardrobe. and they' b'were fighting right down there on the street near the building they were' b'blowing up buses and tanks, and cars were burning, and there were many dead in' b'the courtyard. they drove without looking to see if it was a sidewalk or a' b"street, they just drove, and the ones who didn't manage to get out of the way" b'were run over by the tanks. and when we left--it was evening, it was already' b'dark--there were three buses, and one of them had soldiers in it. mamma ran up' b'and said, "get your clothes on, let\'s go." gaya was wearing slippers, and i' b'had on my blue dress, but it was an old one. i was wearing my old jacket, my' b'old dress, and slippers. and nothing else. gaya had on a skirt, her angora' b'sweater, and slippers. it was raining hard, and there were puddles on the' b'street. they gave mamma an old coat because she was wearing a short-sleeved' b'dress; she put it on and we ran out. we got onto the bus and i was hungry, one' b'of the soldiers from yerevan gave me rations and carried me from one bus to' b"the other in his arms. i gave him the little glass that remained from vika's" b'trousseau, and he gave me his telephone number.' b'' b'-gayane: in the bus there was a soldier with a shield sitting at every window.' b'we had to be ready for anything. they took us to the city party committee, let' b'us out, and then took us into the city party committee building under armed' b'guard. it was jammed with people and you couldn\'t breathe. we asked, "are' b'these all us? armenians?" they answered yes. we were surprised that there were' b"so many armenians in sumgait. all those years we lived there and didn't know" b'there were so many armenians, we were struck by that, we had never' b'noticed. going downstairs the next day i ran into the secretary of the' b"komsomol from vika's plant, the khimprom. he said that vika was alive and" b'well. when i told mamma she of course calmed down some more. but you know,' b'after all that it was hard to believe anything, our faith in everything was' b"just gone. she didn't believe it completely." b'' b"-zinaida: i didn't believe it because i had heard all kinds of things. when" b'we arrived at the city party committee we heard everything imaginable! it' b'was the fear of god. i saw many of our acquaintances, they were kissing each' b'other and asking how their children and homes were. many people already knew' b'that there had been a pogrom of our apartment. they had seen the broken' b"windows. i cried, saying that i didn't know where vika was. one woman said" b"that they had taken two of her daughters and that she couldn't find one of" b'them; the other had been slashed all over. a second said that her husband and' b'her son had been murdered. that was nelli aramian. she lived in building in' b'our microdistrict. they killed her husband, armo, and her son artur. i heard' b'so many things like that that i was already starting to lose touch; my' b'patience had run dry waiting for my daughter. later an azerbaijani fellow came' b"to me and said, aunt zina, vika sent me, she's alive and well and hidden in a" b"safe place; if you want i'll call her there and you can speak with her. we" b'went downstairs to the first floor and he called vika. i spoke with her, heard' b'the voice of my child. she had managed to survive in that hell. then i started' b'begging that azerbaijani to bring her to the city party committee. he tried to' b'talk me out of it: "i\'ll bring her wherever you go, don\'t worry, i\'ve looked' b'after her better than a brother does a sister." all the same i asked him to' b'get her. he brought her and i calmed down. on the second day there was a' b'meeting with demichev [member of the politburo of the central committee of the' b'communist party of the ussr,] and people started shouting. one shouted, "give' b'me my son back!", another yelled, "where is my daughter?!", a third wanted her' b'husband bagirov was there too, and he stood there blinking, not saying' b'anything.' b'' b'-gayane: when demichev asked where we wanted to go, everyone shouted, "to' b'russia!" to be honest we were all frightened of armenia, there were such wild' b'rumors it was as though we were in a terrible dream, and no one wanted to go' b"to armenia. but he said that he couldn't evacuate people to russia and" b'that he would meet with everyone individually the next day and speak with' b'them. and he also said that today he was going to go look at all of our' b'apartments. on march we went to the military barracks in the village of' b'nasosny. we were taken care of marvelously by the military. they sent special' b'flights of children right from there to minvody, yerevan, and moscow. one' b'woman left for moscow with a letter for gorbachev and gromyko.' b'' b'-zinaida: the worst was truly behind us by then. everything had passed, but' b'the pain will remain for our whole lives. it cannot be forgotten. under no' b'circumstances should we, our children, or our grandchildren forget. who will' b'answer for those who died? for our mothers, sisters, brother, sons and' b'daughters? who will bear the responsibility? who will wash away their blood?' b'someone should be made to answer, and severely, so it has an effect on the' b"people that did with us as they pleased it isn't over yet, now we live" b"here, in armenia, protected, but the issue isn't resolved. we would like" b'to stay in armenia, in our homeland, so that all the armenian people will be' b"united. then we will be invincible. armenians won't be scattered throughout" b"the soviet union, about the world, and if we're all together this won't happen" b'again. as a mother of three children, as a woman, as a sister, i ask armenians' b'to be united so that what happened in sumgait will never happen again. our' b'homeland the only request we have is that we be helped in obtaining an' b'apartment and getting jobs. so that our children can work for the good of' b"armenia. if we aren't able to, then let our children do it. and if it's" b"possible, we'll work for the good of armenia too. this is the land of our" b'forefathers. our grandfathers and great-grandfathers lived here too, it was' b'only later that people dispersed all over. like a mother, the land here bore' b'and reared us. it is our wife, and will protect us, too. i want but one thing:' b'that our people never see the hardship that our children saw, that your' b'children here, in armenia, never see anything like it.' b'' b'may b'yerevan' b'- reference b'' b'[1] _the sumgait tragedy; pogroms against armenians in soviet azerbaijan,' b'volume i, eyewitness accounts_, edited by samuel shahmuradian, forward by' b'yelena bonner, publish